instructions:
## Set up TanStack Query (React Query) v5 in Next.js

### 1. Install packages
- Run: `npm install @tanstack/react-query`
- Optionally install devtools: `npm install -D @tanstack/react-query-devtools`
- IMPORTANT: TanStack Query v5 has a completely different API from v4 — do NOT mix v4 docs with v5 code.

### 2. Create a QueryClient provider component
- Create `src/providers/query-provider.tsx` (must be a Client Component):
```tsx
'use client';

import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { ReactQueryDevtools } from '@tanstack/react-query-devtools';
import { useState } from 'react';

export function QueryProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [queryClient] = useState(
    () =>
      new QueryClient({
        defaultOptions: {
          queries: {
            staleTime: 60 * 1000, // 1 minute
          },
        },
      })
  );

  return (
    <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
      {children}
      <ReactQueryDevtools initialIsOpen={false} />
    </QueryClientProvider>
  );
}
```
- IMPORTANT: Create `QueryClient` inside `useState` — NOT at module level. Module-level clients are shared across requests on the server and cause data leaks between users.

### 3. Wrap the root layout
- Update `src/app/layout.tsx` to include the provider:
```tsx
import { QueryProvider } from '@/providers/query-provider';

export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body>
        <QueryProvider>{children}</QueryProvider>
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}
```

### 4. Create typed query functions (API layer)
- Separate fetch logic from UI — create `src/lib/api/posts.ts`:
```ts
export type Post = {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
};

export async function getPosts(): Promise<Post[]> {
  const res = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts');
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch posts');
  return res.json();
}

export async function getPost(id: number): Promise<Post> {
  const res = await fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}`);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`Failed to fetch post ${id}`);
  return res.json();
}
```

### 5. Use useQuery in a Client Component
- Create `src/components/posts-list.tsx`:
```tsx
'use client';

import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { getPosts } from '@/lib/api/posts';

export function PostsList() {
  const { data, isPending, isError, error } = useQuery({
    queryKey: ['posts'],
    queryFn: getPosts,
  });

  if (isPending) return <div>Loading...</div>;
  if (isError) return <div>Error: {error.message}</div>;

  return (
    <ul>
      {data.map((post) => (
        <li key={post.id}>{post.title}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```
- IMPORTANT: In v5, `isLoading` was renamed to `isPending` for queries without data. Use `isPending` for the initial load state.

### 6. Use useMutation for writes
- Add mutation support in a Client Component:
```tsx
'use client';

import { useMutation, useQueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';

async function createPost(data: { title: string; body: string }) {
  const res = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify(data),
  });
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to create post');
  return res.json();
}

export function CreatePostForm() {
  const queryClient = useQueryClient();

  const mutation = useMutation({
    mutationFn: createPost,
    onSuccess: () => {
      // Invalidate and refetch the posts list
      queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['posts'] });
    },
  });

  return (
    <button
      onClick={() => mutation.mutate({ title: 'New Post', body: 'Content here' })}
      disabled={mutation.isPending}
    >
      {mutation.isPending ? 'Creating...' : 'Create Post'}
    </button>
  );
}
```

### 7. Define query key factories (for large apps)
- Avoid raw string arrays scattered across files — create `src/lib/query-keys.ts`:
```ts
export const postKeys = {
  all: ['posts'] as const,
  lists: () => [...postKeys.all, 'list'] as const,
  detail: (id: number) => [...postKeys.all, 'detail', id] as const,
};
```
- Use as: `queryKey: postKeys.lists()` and `queryKey: postKeys.detail(id)`.
- Calling `queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: postKeys.all })` will invalidate all post queries (lists + details).

### 8. Server-side prefetching (optional but recommended)
- Prefetch on the server in a Server Component, then hydrate on the client:
```tsx
// src/app/posts/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { dehydrate, HydrationBoundary, QueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { getPosts } from '@/lib/api/posts';
import { PostsList } from '@/components/posts-list';

export default async function PostsPage() {
  const queryClient = new QueryClient();

  await queryClient.prefetchQuery({
    queryKey: ['posts'],
    queryFn: getPosts,
  });

  return (
    <HydrationBoundary state={dehydrate(queryClient)}>
      <PostsList />
    </HydrationBoundary>
  );
}
```
- The client will hydrate from the prefetched data — no loading spinner on first render.

### 9. Verify the setup
- Run `npm run dev` and navigate to the page using TanStack Query.
- Open browser devtools → TanStack Query Devtools panel (the floating logo icon).
- Confirm queries appear, cache entries are visible, and data loads correctly.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`useQuery` called outside `QueryClientProvider`** — You forgot to wrap the component tree with `<QueryProvider>`. Ensure `layout.tsx` includes the provider.
- **`QueryClient` created at module level** — This causes server-side data leaks between users. Always create inside `useState`.
- **`isLoading` is always `false` on initial render** — In v5, use `isPending` instead of `isLoading` for queries with no data yet. `isLoading` is `isPending && isFetching`.
- **`data` is `undefined` even after `isPending` is false** — Check that `queryFn` actually resolves with data and does not return `undefined` or `null` unexpectedly.
- **Stale data served to every request** — You instantiated `QueryClient` outside `useState`. Each render re-uses the same shared client and its stale cache.
- **`onSuccess` / `onError` callbacks on `useQuery` are missing** — These were removed in v5. Use `useEffect` watching `isSuccess`/`isError`, or put side effects in `useMutation`'s `onSuccess`/`onError`.
- **TypeScript: `data` inferred as `unknown`** — Type your `queryFn` return type explicitly, or use a generic: `useQuery<Post[]>({ ... })`.
- **Infinite refetching loop** — An unstable `queryKey` (object literal recreated each render) triggers a refetch on every render. Use stable primitives or memoized arrays as query keys.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT create `QueryClient` at module level — it is shared across server requests and leaks data between users.
- Do NOT use TanStack Query for data that belongs in a global UI store (e.g., theme, current user preferences) — use Zustand or React Context for client-only UI state.
- Do NOT call `useQuery` directly in Server Components — TanStack Query is a client-side library; use `prefetchQuery` + `HydrationBoundary` for SSR, and `useQuery` in Client Components.
- Do NOT ignore error states — always handle `isError` and display a meaningful message to users.
- Do NOT use raw string query keys like `['posts', userId]` spread across files — centralize in a query key factory to prevent typos and simplify invalidation.
- Do NOT mix v4 and v5 APIs — the `onSuccess`/`onError` callbacks on `useQuery`, `cacheTime` (now `gcTime`), and `isLoading` semantics all changed in v5.
